# {{title}}

<p class="lead">This year's installment of Europe's best information architecture gathering was my second visit. I was happy to have a similar takeaway: [EuroIA](https://euroia.org/) has been a great way to check my perspectives, infuse them with the views of others and step back, dwell on the point of all this.</p>

I was fortunate enough to be one of three staffers from EMBL-EBI — and one of two with the Web Development team — to attend this year's Euro IA conference in Stockholm, and aside from the general fantastic food, views and culture of Sweden and Stockholm, here's a sprinkling of personal highlights from EuroIA.

Colouring my notes is that this year was also an opportunity to dwell on ideas [we](https://blogs.embl.org/communications/tag/design)'ve been discussing [in the EMBL Corporate Design Sprints](https://blogs.embl.org/communications/tag/design/), particularly those around a pan-organisation IA. At any rate, onto my highlights:

## 1. Keep it flexible, be an enabler

